<div class="prose-content max-w-3xl">

  <h2>Ask your pharmacist first</h2>
  <p>Your pharmacist is an expert in medicines and can answer many questions without you needing an appointment with us. They can advise on:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Side effects of your medication</li>
    <li>Whether your medication is safe to take with others</li>
    <li>How and when to take your medication</li>
    <li>Over-the-counter treatments for common conditions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Pharmacists are available in person at your local pharmacy, and many offer a private consultation area.</p>

  <h2>Contact us</h2>
  <p>If your query cannot be answered by a pharmacist, or you have a concern about your prescribed treatment, please contact us:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Telephone:</strong> <a href="tel:{{ site.phone | replace(' ', '') }}">{{ site.phone }}</a> — Monday to Friday, 08:00 to 18:00</li>
    <li><strong>Email:</strong> <a href="mailto:{{ site.email }}">{{ site.email }}</a></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Please do not email urgent medical queries. If you are concerned about a reaction to medication, call us or NHS 24 on 111.</p>

  <h2>Changing or stopping medication</h2>
  <p>Do not stop taking prescribed medication without speaking to a clinician first. If you'd like to discuss your medication, book an appointment or call us during opening hours.</p>

  <h2>NHS Inform — medication advice</h2>
  <p><a href="https://www.nhsinform.scot/tests-and-treatments/medicines-and-medical-aids/medicines/" rel="noopener noreferrer">NHS Inform</a> has reliable information about many common medicines, including what they're used for and possible side effects.</p>

</div>
